The paper discusses the application of compressed sensing techniques to the MUSIC algorithm for imaging sparse extended objects with noisy data. This involves analyzing the restricted isometry property and restricted isometry constant, which are commonly studied in the information theory (cs.IT) and signal processing (cs.SP) sub-categories. The paper also discusses the use of thresholding and basis pursuit denoising, which are common techniques in the sparse signal processing (cs.SI) sub-category. Additionally, the paper involves numerical simulations and analysis of imaging performance, which are common in the numerical analysis (cs.NA) and computer vision (cs.CV) sub-categories. Therefore, the most likely sub-categories are cs.IT, cs.SI, cs.SP, cs.NA, and cs.CV, in that order.
